03851nam a22006615i 9780271062228DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20212013pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710622287 a10.1515/97802710622282doi  a(DE-B1597)584568  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aJC423b.L88 2013eb 7aLAN0040002bisacsh04a321.82231 aLyon, Arabella, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDeliberative Acts :bDemocracy, Rhetoric, and Rights /cArabella Lyon. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (232 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRhetoric and Democratic Deliberation ;v700tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: deliberation in the global era -- t1 Defining deliberative space: rethinking persuasion, position, and identification -- t2 Performative deliberation and the narratable who -- t3 Narrating rights, creating agents: missing women in the U.S. media -- t4 The beauty of Arendt's lies: Menchú's political strategy -- t5 Voting like a girl: declarations, paradoxes of deliberation, and embodied citizens as a difference in kind -- tNotes -- tWorks cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe twenty-first century is characterized by the global circulation of cultures, norms, representations, discourses, and human rights claims; the arising conflicts require innovative understandings of decision making. Deliberative Acts develops a new, cogent theory of performative deliberation. Rather than conceiving deliberation within the familiar frameworks of persuasion, identification, or procedural democracy, it privileges speech acts and bodily enactments that constitute deliberation itself, reorienting deliberative theory toward the initiating moment of recognition, a moment in which interlocutors are positioned in relationship to each other and so may begin to construct a new lifeworld. By approaching human rights not as norms or laws, but as deliberative acts, Lyon conceives rights as relationships among people and as ongoing political and historical projects developing communal norms through global and cross-cultural interactions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aDeliberative democracy. 0aHuman rights. 0aPerformative (Philosophy). 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Communication Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271062228423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271062228.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK